===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Originally {{zh-l|*㢟}}, an {{Han compound|ls=ic|彳|止|t1=walking|t2=foot|nocap=yes}} – "to travel far". The stroke at the top started being added as a distinguishing mark at the end of the {{w|Warring States period}}, as a way to distinguish its usage from {{lang|zh|㢟}} as an adverb to mean "prolonged", making it an {{liushu|i}}.<ref>季旭昇，2004《說文新證》，台北：藝文印書館印行，2014年9月第二版。p.137-138</ref><ref>李學勤) (2012) 《字源》, Tianjin: 天津古籍出版社。p.142-143</ref><ref>[https://humanum.arts.cuhk.edu.hk/Lexis/lexi-mf/search.php?word=%E5%BB%B6 漢語多功能字庫 (Multi-function Chinese Character Database) - 字頭 「延」]</ref>

{{w|Shuowen Jiezi}} interprets it as {{Han compound|丿|㢟|c1=p|c2=s|ls=psc|nocap=yes}}.

===Etymology===
Within Chinese, cognate with {{och-l|筵|bamboo mat}}, {{och-l|梴|long (of wood)}} and {{och-l|誕|wide; ludicrous}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Cognate with {{cog|my|လှန်း||to dry (things) in the sun}}. Probably unrelated to {{ncog|tbq-pro|*jaːr||spread; extend; sail}}, whence {{ncog|bo|གཡོར་མོ||sail}}, {{ncog|lus|zâr||to spread; to spread out}}, {{ncog|kac|yàn||spread; unrolled}}.

{{zh-ref|Pan (1987)}} suggests {{cog|vi|lan||to spread}} is borrowed from Old Chinese {{och-l|延}}.

